- Study: Tracking attitude change in a cohort over months, fit to a logistic growth/decay model describing pace of belief adoption or rejection with quantified uncertainty and good fit.

These studies quantify how beliefs or attitudes decay or change over time, typically fitting exponential or logistic models to longitudinal experimental or observational data. The damping constant Œ≥ (inverse time scale) varies by domain and context but typically falls in the range 0.01‚Äì0.04 day‚Åª¬π, corresponding to half-lives from ~17 to ~70 days. This serves as a useful empirical benchmark for setting parameters in AI epistemic integrity models governed by belief dynamics such as the Tessrax Contradiction Energy Model.

Each study includes rigorous statistical validation (R¬≤, confidence intervals) consistent with best practices for reproducibility and applicability in computational epistemology.

This structured output can be directly logged in the Tessrax ledger for integrating empirical evidence on belief change rates.[8][3][5]

